									<p style="color:#000;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:18px;line-height:28px;margin:0 0 10px 0;padding:0 0 18px 0;clear:both">It’s my birthday today, which means, among other things, that I have just one year left in which I can use Wigmore Hall’s £5 tickets for the under-35s. (I have a special affection for Wigmore Hall, the only London cultural institution that still considers me to be young: however, because the auditorium is so warm I have occasionally nodded off during very beautiful passages of string music, a habit that marks me out as very old indeed.) </p>
									<p style="color:#000;font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:18px;line-height:28px;margin:0 0 10px 0;padding:0 0 18px 0;clear:both">In a poor start to my last year of £5 tickets, my regular D&amp;D group conflicts with <a href="https://www.wigmore-hall.org.uk/whats-on/202403261930" target="_blank">this very good-looking concert by the Nash Ensemble next week</a>. Tonight I’m off to the South Bank to see Tchaikovsky’s fifth symphony, which I’m very much looking forward to. </p>
